{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e3ab3876-8994-480e-8291-f09d5052dea3","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` isn't a standard .NET MAUI property — that's likely why it has no effect. You need **platform-specific** configuration:\n\n**iOS** — Add the platform-specific namespace and disable safe area on the page:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n**Android** — Content doesn't go behind system bars by default (pre-Android 15). In your `MainActivity.cs`, opt into edge-to-edge:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n    \n    if (Window != null)\n    {\n        WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n    }\n}\n```\n\nYou'll need `using AndroidX.Core.View;` for that call.\n\n**Key points:**\n- `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` removes iOS safe area insets\n- `WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(..., false)` lets Android draw behind status/nav bars\n- Android 15+ enforces edge-to-edge automatically, so this mainly helps older versions\n- Use `Aspect=\"AspectFill\"` on the Image so it fills without distortion","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3ce439ab-de87-47de-aabb-16c9a8c8ae61","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app, going behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is a common .NET MAUI question. The key issue is that `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` alone isn't enough — you also need to opt into edge-to-edge rendering at the platform level.\n\nIn .NET MAUI / .NET 10, there are a few things to consider:\n\n1. **`IgnoreSafeArea`** on the view itself — In .NET MAUI, individual views have an `IgnoreSafeArea` property that needs to be set to `true`.\n\n\n2. **Platform-specific configuration** — On iOS, you can disable safe area handling with platform-specific markup, while on Android you need to configure the window to render behind system bars for true edge-to-edge display.\n\nI'm realizing `SafeAreaEdges` isn't actually a standard MAUI property. The correct approach is using platform-specific configuration: on iOS, the `UseSafeArea` property set to false, and on Android, enabling edge-to-edge mode which is now enforced on newer versions. For Android, I need to handle edge-to-edge display by configuring it in the MainActivity or through platform-specific styles, typically using `WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows` or similar APIs depending on the .NET MAUI version.","outputTokens":1263,"requestId":"E831:171772:268E33A:2AB9414:69F942A4"},"id":"43038c62-f120-4b2c-904f-69cc8bf4c87a","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:07:09.774Z","parentId":"23a84b39-6293-4ef1-8253-41a5d904e7b3"}
